The  duties  and  responsibilities  of  the  internal  audit  unit,  as outlined in the Internal Audit Charter are as follows:

- 1. Formulating a flexible Annual Audit Plan using a risk-based approach, subsequently subject to review and approval by the  President  Director  and  the  Board  of  Commissioners, possibly represented by the Audit Committee;
- 2.  Implementing the approved Annual Audit Plan directed by the President Director and conducting special audits upon request from management and the Audit Committee;
- 3. Sustaining the professionalism of internal auditors by ensuring adequate knowledge, skills, experience, and professional certifications;
- 4.  Regularly  reporting  a  summary  of  audit  findings  to  the President Director, the Board of Commissioners, potentially represented by the Audit Committee, and relevant management.
- 5. Providing  consulting  services  to  line  management,  such as  facilitating  risk  self-assessment  controls,  assessing  the adequacy  of  internal  controls,  and  advising  management on system/process to be implemented, while internal audit personnel  may  not  assume  management responsibility  for those system/process;
- 6. Implementing  a  quality  assurance  program  to  evaluate the  quality  of  internal  audit  activities,  with  the  results  of the  quality  assurance  program  reported  to  the  President Director;
- 7. Coordinating  with  other  assurance  functions  (e.g.,  health, safety,  legal  compliance,  risk  management,  and  external auditors);
- 8. Facilitating  the  identification  and  evaluation  of  risks,  and implementing a coordinating role in risk management within the company; and
- 9. Conducting  investigative  audits  of  activities  that  indicate fraud  and  reporting  the  results  of  these  audits  to  the President Director.

